<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-219-364  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 219 364.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  March 5 1990 v11 n10 p34(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>911 software development. (developing software in emergencies)(HowDo You Manage When...) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Roetzheim, William.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Most software development managers will find themselves faced witha tight deadline situation at least once in their careers.andP;  Such'emergency' software development makes efficient use of resourcessecondary to speed, but development cannot be accelerated byskipping the design phase.andP;  A tight design hierarchy withprocessing, data interfaces, and structure clearly called out canbreak a development effort into many small tasks which programmerscan accomplish in parallel.andP;  Completely parallel development, inwhich two individuals or teams are assigned to a single module, iscostly but reduces errors.andP;  Management promises of 'highestpriority' on resources are usually invalid, and the programmingmanager must continue fighting for everything needed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     System DevelopmentSoftware EngineeringProgramming ManagementCrisis ManagementProject Life Cycle.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>